GemLife Communities Group (GLFAX) Price Target Base Case Updated Components EPS
Risk Reward for GemLife Communities Group (GLFAX) has been updated

We have updated our GLF forecasts following the company's inaugural 1H25 results. Overall, 1H25 EBITDA beat prospectus/MSe due to higher settlements (119 actual vs 117 MSe), higher price, and lower OHs, while D&A also came in below guidance. We have extended some of these savings (OHs, D&A) into 2H25+, however, we retain a conservative approach to settlements with no change to our original forecasts (214 lots in 2H25, 382 in FY26, 432 in FY27). Our FY26e OPAT is now A \(86.5m\) (was A \(82.9m\) ).

GLF now has 233 contracts on hand, providing strong visibility over 2H25 settlements. However, GLF has maintained guidance as: (i) there may be some slippage due to weather; and (ii) c.100 of these contracts are still conditional; and (iii) some contracted homes are slated for 2026 completions, so there is still some fluidity around timing, but also potential upside if sales rates remain strong.
We lift our PT to A \(\) 5.40\(was\) \ \(5.35\) driven by the slightly higher cash flow forecasts to our base case DCF.
MORGAN STANLEY AUSTRALIA LIMITED+

Land lease pure- play; resi pure- play
Key: - Historical Stock Performance Current Stock Price Price Target

GLF is an Australian developer of land lease communities, with operations mainly in Queensland. The company makes money predominantly from two sources, (i) rental income from land lease, and (ii) development profit from the building of homes that are in the communities/resorts, targeted at residents over 50 years of age.

GLF offers investors leverage to the residential cycle, given its purchasers are cash buyers, generally funded by the sale of their existing homes. As we head into a period of higher home purchasing power, higher house price, and lower (relative to 2022- early 2025) mortgage rates, the outlook bodes well for GLF.
